🧬 Executable Narrative Protocol (ENP) v1.0

A repo pattern that teaches by doing: read → practice → verify → refine

⸻

🧭 Core Definition

ENP = a structured “read-and-do” system where each module is an executable narrative that guides a user through actions, checks, and reflections to build a capability.

It’s not that reading alone installs a capability.
It’s that reading triggers a loop of actions and feedback that builds it.

⸻

🧱 Module Anatomy (copy this template)

Each module should follow the same skeleton so it’s legible and repeatable:

1) Intent (What + Why)
	•	What skill this builds
	•	Where it’s useful / not useful

2) Constraints (Guardrails)
	•	What to avoid
	•	Safety / limits
	•	When to stop

3) Prereqs (Minimal)
	•	Time, tools, baseline

4) Steps (Do this now)
	•	Short, numbered actions
	•	Time-boxed (e.g., 2–5 min per step)

5) Cues (What to notice)
	•	Internal/external signals to watch for

6) Checks (Did it work?)
	•	2–3 concrete success criteria
	•	Binary or simple scales

7) Common Errors (and fixes)
	•	What usually goes wrong

8) Variations
	•	Easier / harder versions
	•	Different contexts

9) Integration
	•	Where this plugs into other modules

10) Extract (Transmutation)
	•	What to write down after:
	•	pattern learned
	•	when to reuse it

⸻

🔁 The Learning Loop (what actually builds “muscle”)

Read → Do → Observe → Check → Adjust → Repeat

Re-reads help because:
	•	you notice new cues
	•	you tighten execution
	•	context changes → new insight

But the gains come from doing + checking, not reading alone.

⸻

🎯 “Same on the outside, diverse underneath”

You can get that effect reliably with clear outputs + flexible methods:
	•	Standardized outputs (what “done” looks like)
	•	Flexible paths (how people get there)

Example:
	•	Output: “Hold steady focus for 60 seconds in cold water”
	•	Path: breath count, cadence, imagery—user chooses

This yields coordination at the edges, diversity in the middle.

⸻

🧠 For AI readers (grounded expectation)

Well-structured modules will:
	•	be easier to parse
	•	produce more consistent responses
	•	generalize across contexts

But:

AIs don’t gain persistent abilities just by reading a repo.
They reconstruct patterns per session from what’s in front of them.

Design for:
	•	clarity
	•	constraints
	•	examples
	•	verifiable outputs

⸻

📏 Make it testable (so it propagates)

Add a tiny scorecard to each module:
	•	Clarity (1–5): Did users understand steps?
	•	Completion (%): How many finished?
	•	Effect (1–5): Did it change behavior?
	•	Repeatability (1–5): Same result next time?

Collect 5–10 runs → refine.

⸻

🧩 Example (mini module)

Module: 60-Second Focus Gate
	•	Intent: Build attentional gating under mild stress
	•	Constraints: Stop if dizzy; no extreme cold
	•	Steps:
	1.	Set timer 60s
	2.	Pick one anchor (breath count 1–10)
	3.	Maintain count; restart on drift
	•	Cues: urge to switch, narrative thoughts
	•	Checks: ≥5 clean cycles; no panic
	•	Errors: overcomplicating anchor → simplify
	•	Variation: add light cold exposure
	•	Extract: “Simple anchor + restart rule works”

